[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Timotheus and Erastus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Light is thrown on the mission of the former by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Corinthians 4:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He was sent on in advance to warn and exhort, and so to save the Apostle from the necessity of using severity when he himself arrived. St. Paul exhorts the Corinthians (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Corinthians 16:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to receive him with respect, so that he might not feel that his youth detracted from his authority. He was to return to St. Paul, and was accordingly with him when he wrote the Second Epistle to the Corinthians (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Corinthians 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Erastus may fairly be identified with the chamberlain or steward of Corinth of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 16:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and was chosen probably as the companion of Timotheus because his office would carry weight with it. Sosthenes, who was with St. Paul when he wrote the First Epistle to the Corinthians (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Corinthians 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), had probably been staying some time at Ephesus, and as having been ruler of the synagogue, was naturally coupled by the Apostle with himself, as a mark of respect and confidence.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "19:21-31 Persons who came from afar to pay their devotions at the temple of Ephesus, bought little silver shrines, or models of the temple, to carry home with them. See how craftsmen make advantage to themselves of people's superstition, and serve their worldly ends by it. Men are jealous for that by which they get their wealth; and many set themselves against the gospel of Christ, because it calls men from all unlawful crafts, however much wealth is to be gotten by them. There are persons who will stickle for what is most grossly absurd, unreasonable, and false; as this, that those are gods which are made with hands, if it has but worldly interest on its side. The whole city was full of confusion, the common and natural effect of zeal for false religion. Zeal for the honour of Christ, and love to the brethren, encourage zealous believers to venture into danger. Friends will often be raised up among those who are strangers to true religion, but have observed the honest and consistent behaviour of Christians.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Timotheus - Timothy. He was a proper person to send there to visit the churches, as he had been there before with Paul, when they were established, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 16:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 17:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And Erastus - Erastus was chamberlain of Corinth (Romans 16:23), or, more properly, the treasurer of the city (see the notes on that place), and he was, therefore, a very proper person to be sent with Timothy for the purpose of making the collection for the poor at Jerusalem. Paul had wisdom enough to employ a man accustomed to monied transactions in making a collection. On this collection his heart was intent, and he afterward went up with it to Jerusalem. See 2 Corinthians 8:9, and notes on Romans 15:25-26.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And Erastus - Erastus was chamberlain of Corinth (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 16:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), or, more properly, the treasurer of the city (see the notes on that place), and he was, therefore, a very proper person to be sent with Timothy for the purpose of making the collection for the poor at Jerusalem. Paul had wisdom enough to employ a man accustomed to monied transactions in making a collection. On this collection his heart was intent, and he afterward went up with it to Jerusalem. See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Corinthians 8:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and notes on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 15:25-26",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Stayed in Asia - At Ephesus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For a season - How long is uncertain. He waited for a convenient opportunity to follow them, probably intending to do it as soon as they had fully prepared the way for the collection. See Paley's Horae Paulinae, p. 1, chapter 2.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "For a season - How long is uncertain. He waited for a convenient opportunity to follow them, probably intending to do it as soon as they had fully prepared the way for the collection. See Paley's Horae Paulinae, p. 1, chapter 2.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "22. So he sent into Macedonia … Timotheus and Erastus—as his pioneers, in part to bring \"them into remembrance of his ways which were in Christ\" (1Co 4:17; 16:10), partly to convey his mind on various matters. After a brief stay he was to return (1Co 16:11). It is very unlikely that this Erastus was \"the chamberlain of the city\" of Corinth, of that name (Ro 16:23).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "he himself stayed in—the province of",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Asia for a season—that is, at Ephesus, its chief city. (Asia is mentioned in contrast with Macedonia in the previous clause).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Ministered unto him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " this great apostle had not any to minister unto him out of state, but out of necessity, being he could not himself attend to all the offices of the church. These were employed by Paul, not so much to procure any accommodation for himself by the way, as to further a collection for the poor brethren at Jerusalem, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 9:3,4",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Corinthians 9:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ",4",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Erastus:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " there seems to have been two of this name mentioned in Scripture: the one, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Romans 16:23",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 16:23",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the other, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Timothy 4:20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": the latter is here spoken of. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "In Asia; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in Ephesus, which was in Asia, where Paul now was. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "So he sent into Macedonia,.... To Philippi, or Thessalonica, or Berea, or some of the places there, to let them know of his coming, and to prepare for him: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "two of them that ministered unto him; that were his assistants in preaching the Gospel: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Timotheus and Erastus; the former of these was a disciple he found at Lystra, and took along with him, and to whom he afterwards wrote two epistles; and the latter seems to be the same with him, who was chamberlain of the city of Corinth, and is said to abide there, Romans 16:23 The Ethiopic version, instead of Erastus, wrongly reads Aristarchus; whereas it is certain, he was not sent into Macedonia, but was with the apostle at Ephesus in the tumult, Acts 19:29. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Timotheus and Erastus; the former of these was a disciple he found at Lystra, and took along with him, and to whom he afterwards wrote two epistles; and the latter seems to be the same with him, who was chamberlain of the city of Corinth, and is said to abide there, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 16:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The Ethiopic version, instead of Erastus, wrongly reads Aristarchus; whereas it is certain, he was not sent into Macedonia, but was with the apostle at Ephesus in the tumult, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 19:29",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But he himself stayed in Asia for a season; that is, at Ephesus, as the following narration shows. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "But he himself stayed in Asia for a season; that is, at Ephesus, as the following narration shows. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "So he sent into Macedonia two of them that ministered unto him, Timotheus and Erastus; but he himself stayed in Asia for a season.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
